# Suteki Shop – ASP.NET MVC eCommerce Application

Suteki Shop is a full-featured eCommerce web application originally designed for a fashion retail business.  
The application provides a product catalogue, shopping cart, and order processing system built with ASP.NET MVC.

Repository: https://github.com/keithevans1019/aspnet-mvc-suteki-ecommerce

---

## Overview

This project demonstrates how to build a traditional eCommerce platform using ASP.NET MVC and .NET Framework.

The system was originally designed for fashion retail businesses and includes essential online store functionality such as product browsing, cart management, and order processing.

The application follows good software engineering practices and was developed using Test Driven Development (TDD).

---

## Core Features

- Product catalogue management
- Category-based product browsing
- Shopping cart functionality
- Order processing workflow
- Administrator management interface
- Category and product administration
- Database-driven product management

---

## Technology Stack

### Backend

- .NET Framework 4.0
- ASP.NET MVC 3
- NHibernate ORM
- Windsor IoC Container
- MVC Contrib

### Testing

- NUnit
- Rhino Mocks
- Test Driven Development (TDD)

### Database

- SQL Server

---

## Project Architecture

The system uses a layered architecture designed to separate concerns across the application.

Key architectural components include:

- MVC presentation layer
- Domain-driven business logic
- Data access using NHibernate ORM
- Dependency injection using Windsor IoC container
- Automated testing using NUnit and Rhino Mocks

This architecture allows the system to remain maintainable and scalable.

---

## Development Requirements

To work with the project source code you will need:

- Visual Studio 2010
- SQL Server 2008 or later
- .NET Framework 4.0

---

## Building the Project

1. Open the solution file in Visual Studio.
2. Restore any required dependencies.
3. Build the solution.

If the environment is configured correctly the solution should build successfully.

---

## Database Setup

Before running the application, the database must be created.

The project includes a database creation utility that initializes the database and inserts required static data.

Steps:

1. Check the database connection string in the configuration file.
2. Ensure the connection has permission to create databases.
3. Run the database creation console project.

After successful execution the database will be created and initialized.

---

## Running the Application

Once the database has been created:

1. Launch the main web application project.
2. The application should start and display the storefront.
3. Administrator access allows category and product management.

---

## Admin Access

Administrator access allows management of the store including:

- Adding categories
- Managing products
- Maintaining catalog structure

The administrator account can be used to configure the store and manage inventory.

---

## Learning Objectives

This project helps developers understand how to:

- Build an eCommerce system using ASP.NET MVC
- Implement dependency injection with Windsor IoC
- Use NHibernate for data persistence
- Apply Test Driven Development practices
- Structure maintainable enterprise web applications

---

## Disclaimer

This project is provided for educational purposes to demonstrate traditional ASP.NET MVC application architecture and eCommerce development concepts.

